Use this method (and the corresponding

method) to initialize your app and prepare it to run. This method is called after your app has been launched and its main storyboard or nib file has been loaded, but before your app’s state has been restored. At the time this method is called, your app is in the inactive state.
If your app was launched by the system for a specific reason, the

dictionary contains data indicating the reason for the launch. For some launch reasons, the system may call additional methods of your app delegate. For example, if your app was launched to open a URL, the system calls the

method after your app finishes initializing itself. The presence of the launch keys gives you the opportunity to plan for that behavior. In the case of a URL to open, you might want to prevent state restoration if the URL represents a document that the user wanted to open.
When asked to open a URL, the return result from this method is combined with the return result from the
method to determine if a URL should be handled. If either method returns
, the system does not call the
method. If you do not implement one of the methods, only the return value of the implemented method is considered.
In some cases, the user launches your app with a Home screen quick action. To ensure you handle this launch case correctly, read the discussion in the
method.
If your app relies on the state restoration machinery to restore its view controllers, always show your app’s window from this method. Do not show the window in your app’s
method. Calling the window’s
method does not make the window visible right away anyway. UIKit waits until your app’s
method finishes before making the window visible on the screen.

abstract.text: Construct and manage a graphical, event-driven user interface for your iOS, iPadOS, or tvOS app.
The centralized point of control and coordination for apps running in iOS.
The keys you use to access values in the launch options dictionary that the system passes to your app at initialization.
A notification that posts immediately after the app finishes launching.
A set of methods to manage shared behaviors for your app.
Tells the delegate that the launch process is almost done and the app is almost ready to run.
Asks the delegate to open a resource specified by a URL, and provides a dictionary of launch options.
Tells the delegate that the user selected a Home screen quick action for your app, except when you’ve intercepted the interaction in a launch method.
Tells the delegate that the launch process has begun but that state restoration hasn’t occured.
Shows the window and makes it the key window.
